<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 92 / Berlin's 'man with red scarf' quits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE star of Mr Walter Momper, who shot to international prominence as mayor
of Berlin during Germany's unification celebrations, slumped below the
horizon yesterday morning.
'The man with the red scarf' resigned as chairman of the city-state's Social
Democrat party after a short, sharp clash over his new job as general
manager of Ellinghaus, a building and property company with ambitions in the
east.
Complaining of attacks 'bordering on vilification', Mr Momper, 47, said he
had been surprised by the vigour of the assault and claimed enemies had
seized on his new job as an excuse to get rid of him.
His political leadership had not been brought into question and there were
no candidates for his job, he said yesterday. He had recognised the
possibility of a conflict of interests between his new business commitments
and his lifelong political vocation, and had undertaken not to do business
personally in Berlin.
But to no purpose. A week after his new appointment became known, Mr Momper
was out.
He gained local fame in 1989 after rallying quarrelsome SPD factions and
leading the party to a surprise parliamentary victory over the CDU.
For a brief 20 months, as unification loomed, came and went, Mayor Momper
enjoyed popular support and shared the international limelight - never
without his red scarf - in company with Chancellor Helmut Kohl and other
Bonn notables.
But off-stage, his wobbly coalition with the anti-establishment Greens was
unpopular with many SPD stalwarts. Combined with the surge of support for
the CDU which followed the fall of the wall, the internal unrest led to the
SPD suffering its worst-ever result in Berlin at the first pan-German
election in December 1990.
Although the CDU formed a government with the Social Democrats, there was no
place in it for Mr Momper. Holding on as party chairman, he took a back seat
in parliament. Resentments simmered and rivals waited for him to make a
mistake. In the end, he made two.
While Ellinghaus is above reproach, the Berlin property and construction
business is no stranger to scandal and corruption charges. Second, and
possibly worse, Mr Momper's new boss, Mr Gert Ellinghaus, is a member of
Chancellor Kohl's Christian Democrats.
A surprise offer by Germany's DAG white-collar trade union to accept longer
working hours and less pay was revealed yesterday after Sunday's preliminary
pay talks for the 60,000 employees of Lufthansa. The loss-making state
airline, will shortly announce a dramatic cost-cutting programme, expected
to include up to 10,000 job losses.
DAG, said its aim was to help restore Luthansa's fortunes.
