<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 92 / Banks warned of severe staff crisis
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INDUSTRIAL relations in clearing banks are threatened by an unprecedented
mixture of job losses, branch restructuring and truncated promotion
prospects, according to a report to be published this week.
Although banks are attempting to change staff relations policies to cope
with their moves towards increased competitiveness, new tensions and the
breakdown of the old 'paternalism' are putting staff loyalty at risk, the
report says.
'Staff trust in management appears to be at a low ebb, producing the seeds
for future conflicts. The level of resistance, of grievance and of
resentment remains high,' say the study's authors, Mr Peter Cressey, a
sociology lecturer, and Mr Peter Scott, a research officer, both of Bath
University.
The paper points to the significant job losses, with the number employed in
banking as a whole falling from 504,000 in 1990 to 450,000 last year, as one
factor in the destabilisation.
Career structures are also being affected by banks' increased emphasis on
the ability to sell financial products and services to customers. 'There is
considerable resistance among the banks' lower and middle managerial staffs,
aged in their 40s and above, to the idea of the bank administrator as a
salesperson first and foremost,' the report says.
In addition, recruitment is becoming increasingly segmented. As management
and technical services become more specialised, the banks are employing an
increasing number of part-time workers, mainly women, whose promotion
prospects out of clerical jobs are limited.
This latter group is becoming increasingly dissatisfied, says the report.
The study says that each of the 'stabilising pillars of employment levels,
employees' career structure and industrial relations at the banks has
individually been threatened before. What is new is that rather than being
relatively self-contained in their own spheres, they are now interwoven
constituents of a general crisis in employment relations.'
Employment, Technology and Industrial Relations in the UK Clearing Banks, in
New Technology, Work and Employment, Autumn 1992, Vol 7, No 2, Blackwell
Publishers. 0865 791100.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
