<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 92 / Britain prepared to join US in air strikes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH forces are ready to join the US in air strikes against Iraq if the
Baghdad government continues to flout United Nations resolutions, the
government signalled yesterday.
Downing Street officials played down speculation that strikes were imminent.
But they confirmed Mr John Major would discuss the option at a meeting with
senior ministers this morning
UK officials emphasised that Mr Major had yet to make any final decisions.
The prime minister is said to be uncertain whether military action would
require further deliberation at the UN Security Council or whether it would
be authorised under existing resolutions.
Legal experts are expected to clarify the position at today's meeting. But
one senior official said that even if no further resolutions technically
were required, Mr Major would prefer specific UN authorisation for air
strikes.
The officials added that the bombing of military installations and
government buildings was only one of the options under consideration to
force compliance with UN decisions.
Mr Major is interrupting a holiday in Spain to attend today's meeting which
will discuss Iraq as well as next week's international conference on
Yugoslavia.
The officials indicated that the brunt of any military action would be borne
by the US. But UK aircraft could operate from several bases in the region.
The RAF has a small number of Jaguar fighters stationed in Turkey to protect
the safe havens for the Kurds in northern Iraq. Squadrons of Tornado ground
attack aircraft regularly operate from Cyprus and others could be quickly
deployed in Bahrain if the strikes went ahead.
The Royal Navy's three-vessel Armilla Patrol is also in the region and the
Type 42 destroyer HMS Edinburgh is currently involved in a training exercise
with the Kuwaitis.
</TEXT>
