<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 92 / London Stock Exchange: Rally extended in sluggish turnover
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RECOVERY in the UK stock market was extended yesterday as investors
continued to hope that Friday's better news on inflation might open the way
for lower interest rates and thus prompt recovery in European economies.
Equities were helped at the close by reports of a successful outcome to the
auction of government bonds.
However, reports on the UK economy remained unconvincing and yesterday's
buyers of shares appeared to be mostly professionals wanting stock to meet
selling commitments taken on during the market's seven-day slide. The
institutions played a cautious role, and trading volume was thin.
The upturn came in the second half of the session, and was led from the
stock index futures sector when the September future moved towards the 2,400
mark. In the stock market itself, there were further gains among building
and construction shares, and hopes for recovery in the US dollar spurred
rises in dollar-orientated issues.
By the close, the FT-SE Index had put on 19.3 to register 2,376.1, the best
level of the day. Seaq volume, in spite of the improvement in the latter
half of the session, reached a mere 315.3m shares. Friday's total of 449.7m
represented only Pounds 820.2m in retail or genuine investment business.
These volume statistics tend to confirm that the recovery in share prices
since Friday afternoon has been spurred by intra-market business, as
marketmaking houses have competed with one another to buy stock ahead of the
close on Friday of the equity trading account.
Yesterday's session opened uncertainly, with mixed signals coming from the
retail sector. The latest survey of distributive trades from the
Confederation of British Industry reported the worst spending figures for a
decade. However, this was offset by interim results from Argos, the discount
retailer, which disclosed higher sales and some optimistic signs on the
outlook for the rest of the year.
The market lost its early gains but managed to rise again in lacklustre
business. The absence of significant profit-taking after Friday's rally was
encouraging and helped share prices to move forward.
The rebound in building and construction shares came in spite of a report
from the Bank of England that about 1m, or one tenth, of the householders in
the UK now have mortgages greater than the market value of their houses. A
leading UK estate agent reported that building land has lost 62 per cent of
its value over the past three years.
The uncertainty in the stock market was reflected by comments from equity
strategists. Mr Nicholas Knight, the bearish analyst at Nomura Research,
said: 'The knock-out punch is fast approaching in our opinion  - a rise in
UK interest rates.'
UBS Phillips &amp; Drew says its economic forecasts can no longer be described
as sugg-esting modest recovery 'even on the most charitable interpretation'.
Mr Peter Thorne at Nikko, however, believes equities are oversold and
represent 'excellent fundamental value'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 32
</PAGE>
</DOC>
