<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 92 / Major keeps open troops option: Prime minister to interrupt
holiday for emergency talks on Bosnia crisis
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor and JUDY DEMPSEY, Eastern Europe
Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN yesterday left open the possibility that it would contribute ground
troops to protect aid convoys in Bosnia as Mr John Major, the Prime
Minister, announced he was interrupting his holiday for emergency talks on
the crisis.
British officials, however, said Mr Major was as determined as ever that
British troops should not become embroiled in a peacekeeping role in Bosnia,
while President George Bush reiterated that the US would not involve US
troops in any multinational force 'for the time being'.
British officials emphasised that Mr Major's return to London tomorrow from
Spain for talks with senior cabinet colleagues did not signal the imminent
despatch of ground troops to the former Yugoslav republic.
The prime minister instead planned a detailed review of the options
following last week's UN resolution authorising the use of 'all necessary
measures' to ensure that humanitarian aid convoys were protected. The
resolution, watered down by the UK, fell short of advocating military force.
Mr Major's decision to raise the UK government's profile in efforts to
restore peace to the former Yugoslav republic is partly in response to
criticism that his government, which holds the EC presidency, has not done
enough to co-ordinate international action to end the fighting.
His decision coincided with a stinging criticism of Serbia by Mr Douglas
Hogg, the foreign office minister.
Mr Hogg said next week's London peace conference on Yugoslavia, sponsored by
the EC and UN, would make it clear to Serbian leaders that their country
would remain a 'pariah' state until it reversed the policy of 'ethnic
cleansing' in Bosnia.
But a US diplomat in Belgrade yesterday said it was 'naive' to believe that
ethnic cleansing could be reversed, or that the former status quo in Bosnia
could be restored.
EC officials will meet in Brussels today to discuss measures to stop
violations of UN sanctions imposed last May against Serbia and Montenegro,
its remaining ally from the former Yugoslavia, a German Foreign Ministry
spokesman said.
Mr Bush, meanwhile, said during a television interview shown yesterday: 'I
don't want to commit a soldier to battle unless I know that we've got the
wherewithal for them to win, and win fast.' He added: 'The US cannot be the
world's policeman.'
An eight-truck UN relief convoy reached the relative safety of Sarajevo last
night after delivering food to the besieged Bosnian town of Gorazde, a UN
official said. The convoy, which had been delayed on its return by a mined
bridge, was rescued by UN forces. Moslem and Serb forces had refused to
unblock the bridge, a UN spokesman said.
