<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 92 / Middleton set to be Lloyd's chief executive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR PETER MIDDLETON, chief executive of Thomas Cook, the travel subsidiary
recently sold by Midland Bank, is expected to be appointed as the new chief
executive of Lloyd's of London, the insurance market, in the next few weeks.
He was chosen as the preferred candidate for the vacant post at a recent
meeting of the senior appointments committee of Lloyd's Council members from
a shortlist compiled by GKR &amp; Associates, a London-based firm of executive
head-hunters.
Mr Middleton will be formally introduced at the next full council meeting in
early September. Traditionally this has been a formality, as the full
council has no authority over selection for the post.
The new chief executive will work closely with both the chairman and the
head of regulation at Lloyd's. Mr David Coleridge, the previous chairman,
nominated Mr David Rowland, the head of Sedgwick, the insurance company, as
his successor at the annual general meeting last month.
The role of the chief executive is being fundamentally restructured to focus
on 'business development' in line with recommendations from both the Lloyd's
task force report issued in January and in the report chaired by Sir Jeremy
Morse released at the start of July.
Mr Middleton became chief executive of Thomas Cook Group in December 1987,
and helped negotiate the sale of the group for Pounds 200m from Midland to
LTU, Germany's third-largest package tour operator. Much of his past career
was spent at the Foreign and Commonwealth Office.
Mr Middleton is believed to have been chosen over two internal finalists for
the position, Mr Robert Hewes, head of regulatory services, and Mr Andrew
Duguid, head of market services.
His salary is not known, although his predecessor received about Pounds
200,000 a year. Mr Middleton earned more than Pounds 140,000 as chief
executive of Thomas Cook for the financial year ending in 1990.
A note on the skills required for the job by Mr Alan Lord, the previous
chief executive who retired in June, is believed to have stressed the
importance of attendance at committees and preparing papers, which he
believed made a civil servant the preferred choice.
Senior Lloyd's insiders had been concerned at the speed with which a new
chief executive was being chosen, so soon after recommendations for changing
the position's function.
But several said yesterday that they were satisfied with the choice of Mr
Middleton because of his diverse background, including considerable business
experience.
Thomas Cook said yesterday that Mr Middleton was halfway through a
three-week holiday in Italy arranged through the company, and could not be
contacted. 'It is not for any of us to comment on personal matters,' a
spokeswoman said.
</TEXT>
