<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 92 / Revenues from state sell-off may beat target
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT could raise more than the Pounds 8bn expected from
privatisation in the current financial year, giving it scope to consider
raising additional funds to help curb its rising deficit.
Cash already received and funds due from sales that have taken place is set
to yield Pounds 6.74bn of the targeted Pounds 8bn for 1992-93. A further
Pounds 1bn is to be raised from the sale of government loans made to
privatised utility companies, including BT and the electricity sector,
taking it to within Pounds 250m of the target figure.
This could be covered by the repayment of part of a further Pounds 650m
tranche of electricity company debt. The government can take this on to its
books in 1992-93 or 1993-94, allowing a degree of flexibility in its
planning.
The Treasury is not thought to be pushing for extra privatisation cash this
year, over and above the budgeted Pounds 8bn. But pressure to drum up more
money could grow if the public sector borrowing requirement moves too far
above the Pounds 28bn forecast.
The government will not officially revise this forecast ahead of the autumn
statement in November, but a deficit of well over Pounds 30bn is widely
expected because of the severity of the recession and its impact on public
spending and tax revenues.
The Treasury would be reluctant to take privatisation proceeds that would
otherwise accrue in future years simply in order to maximise the present
year's takings.
But analysis of debt and equity assets still owned by the government in
privatised companies suggests it could comfortably realise the Pounds 11bn
of proceeds budgeted for during the next two financial years. This is
without taking into account likely proceeds from the sale of British Coal
and British Rail and the possible sale of part or all of the Post Office.
The government's most valuable stake in a private sector company is its 22
per cent of BT. This could raise more than Pounds 4bn.
Treasury takes stock, Page 5
