<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 92 / Conference agenda reveals Tory unease
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UNEASE among Tory party activists about the depth of the recession has
been confirmed in a series of critical motions tabled for debate at the
party conference in October.
Senior party officials are, however, drawing comfort from assurances by Lady
Thatcher that she has no plans to use the conference to launch a broadside
on Mr John Major's approach to the economy and Europe.
In spite of her public backing for sharp cuts in interest rates and her
fierce opposition to the Maastricht treaty on European union, Lady
Thatcher's aides have indicated that she does not intend to embarrass the
prime minister.
Conservative Central Office has suggested in return that she make a brief
appearance on the conference platform to share the applause of the party
faithful for April's general election victory.
The draft agenda for the Brighton conference, leaked at the weekend,
contains several dozen motions from constituency activists which are openly
or implicitly critical of the government's handling of the economy and
Europe.
Most of the economic motions back the government's determination to defeat
inflation but many then go on to call for a more sympathetic approach to the
plight of small businesses, the housing market and the unemployed.
Among the specific demands are calls for more government help for training
and an extension of the moratorium on stamp duty. A handful demand that
sterling be withdrawn from the European exchange rate mechanism to allow
interest rates to be cut sharply.
A large proportion of the motions on Europe have a similarly equivocal tone,
with support for Mr Major's negotiating stance at Maastricht tinged with the
scepticism of the treaty's opponents. A small number suggest outright
rejection of European union and back Lady Thatcher's call for a referendum
on the treaty.
Ministers were voicing confidence yesterday that the critics could be
'handled' by Mr Major.
</TEXT>
