<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 92 / Edinburgh director confident of success
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE 1992 Edinburgh Festival opened last night with Mr Brian McMaster, who is
directing the festival for the first time, confident that the Pounds 4m cost
will be covered.
Ticket sales, which are planned to achieve 70 per cent of seating capacity,
are slightly below target at nearly Pounds 900,000 but late booking has
become commonplace in the recession and the festival has successfully raised
Pounds 770,000 in sponsorship, the same as last year.
For the next three weeks the Scottish capital will fill with such performers
as American dancers, German actors and Danish musicians among the thousands
of participants in the largest arts festival in the world.
The most persuasive of this year's four main themes at the festival is the
music of Tchaikovsky, with 30 performances of his work, including the
rarely-performed opera The Oprichnik.
There will be an unprecedented concentration of Scottish music, from the 8th
century to the present day. On the final evening of the festival, this will
culminate with a performance by the Scottish Chamber Orchestra of James
MacMillan's new Percussion Concerto written for Evelyn Glennie.
After many years in which foreign drama has dominated the festival the main
feature of the theatrical programme this year is the work of two neglected
British playwrights, the Edwardian Harley Granville Barker, best known for
The Madras House and The Voysey Inheritance, and the Glasgow born CP Taylor,
who wrote Good and Walter.
Other highlights include the first British performance of the Mark Morris
Dance Group from the US and the first for 10 years of the Pina Bausch
company from Germany, Andrei Serban's production of An Ancient Trilogy
performed by his Romanian company in ancient Greek, and Elisabeth Soderstrom
singing Poulenc's opera for solo voice, La Voix Humaine.
The fringe festival this year threatens to be the largest ever with more
than 1,100 different shows.
The television and film festivals will also run alongside the main festival.
</TEXT>
