<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 92 / Developing country competition and unskilled jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEW ECONOMISTS doubt that trade is the route to economic growth for
developing countries. Most also believe that free trade is in the interests
of consumers in developed countries too. But the rise of trade barriers in
industrial countries over the last decade, and their unwillingness to
complete the Uruguay Round, suggest that politicians are not convinced by
the merits of lower trade barriers.
The popular view that competition from low-cost producers in developing
countries pose a growing threat to jobs and incomes in industrial countries
is, instead, gaining ground. Both Ross Perot, the former US presidential
candidate, and senior Democrats in congress have latched on to this fear.
The proposed North American free trade area, signed last week, may yet
flounder over the next few weeks in the face of congressional opposition.
Developing country exports have certainly grown rapidly over the past three
decades, and exports from the east Asian economies have grown even faster:
by an average 9.2 per cent between 1965 and 1980 and 10.2 per cent a year
between 1980 and 1990. The share of developing country goods in total
developed country consumption of manufactures has more than tripled in the
last 25 years.
Yet conventional wisdom among economists says that developing country trade
is too small to have significant negative effects on wages and employment in
developed countries. The penetration of developing country imports into
developed country markets may be growing, but it remains low. Developing
country exports account for less than a 10th of the manufacturing imports of
developed countries and only 3.1 per cent of total manufacturing
consumption, as the chart shows. Even if every developing countries had
posted South Korean style export growth in the 1980s, this share would have
been a mere 0.6 percentage points higher.
The impact of trade on labour-intensive manufacturing industry in developed
countries has been more pronounced. The share of developing country trade in
industrial country imports of these goods has grown from 9.8 per cent in
1965 to 18.7 per cent in 1989 and developing country clothing producers now
account for 22.1 per cent of total clothing consumption in industrial
countries.
Professor Adrian Wood of the Institute of development Studies at Sussex
University has estimated the cumulative effects of developing country trade
on manufacturing employment in industrial countries over the last 30 years.
Skilled employment increases very slightly - the extra jobs created by
higher exports out-weighed the jobs displaced by imports. But for unskilled
employees, the losses swamp the gains. By 1990, total manufacturing
employment was a net 9m jobs lower, as a result.
Still, estimates of the manufacturing employment cost of developing country
trade are not large compared to the actual decline in manufacturing
employment that has occurred. The decline in the share of manufacturing in
total employment in industrial countries, from 29 per cent in the mid 1960s
to 22 per cent in the mid 1980s, implies a loss of 30m jobs.
Yet estimates of lost employment and import penetration ratios ignore the
effect of trade on investment and technical progress. Research in the US
suggests that trade is overwhelmed by domestic factors in explaining the
shift in demand for labour from unskilled to skilled. But companies may
respond to the threat of competition by introducing more advanced production
methods which use less labour. The timing of the acceleration in
manufacturing productivity growth over the last three decades matches the
rise of developing country trade. Productivity growth is largely to blame
for the fall in manufacturing employment in developed countries, accompanied
by rising unemployment and falling relative wages among uneducated workers,
whether or not it can be traced to domestic or external factors; and for the
nervousness of politicians.
'How much does trade with the South affect workers in the North?', World
Bank Research Observer, January 1991.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC INDICATORS: BALANCE OF PAYMENTS
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Trade figures are given in billions of European currency units (Ecu).
The Ecu exchange rate shows the number of national currency units per
Ecu. The nominal effective exchange rate is an index with 1985=100.
