<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 92 / Smaller businesses warn of long slump
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE recession has turned into a slump and is set to last for at least
another two years, according to the Federation of Small Businesses.
The prediction follows a poll the federation conducted last week among 350
small companies and is accompanied by a warning of impending 'catastrophe'
in the sector. The survey found that nearly half of the companies contacted
saw no improvement in projected turnover levels before the end of 1994 at
the earliest.
Companies said a cut in interest rates was the measure most needed to help
combat the recession. The federation forecasts that, if its members' fears
are confirmed, unemployment could double in the next two years.
Mr Ian Handford, the federation's policy unit chairman, said: 'Statements
from the Treasury urging a sit-tight-and-wait policy do nothing to alleviate
the fears of small businesses and destroy any sign of hope or confidence in
the foreseeable future.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
