<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 92 / Waigel tries to calm fears over D-Mark
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GERMANY'S finance minister, Mr Theo Waigel, yesterday sought to reassure the
German people that 'there will be no automatic doing away with the D-Mark.'
The German government takes the worries of ordinary German people about
monetary union and the eventual abolition of the D-Mark very seriously, he
told the mass circulation Bild am Sonntag yesterday.
There would be a full debate in both houses of parliament before the
government took a final decision on European monetary union and the future
of the currency would be decided only with the support of parliament, Mr
Waigel said.
'Even if one day a common currency comes to Europe, the familiar imprint of
the D-Mark will definitely remain on one of side of the new notes and
coins,' he told the newspaper whose sister publication, the daily Bild
Zeitung, lamented the passing of what it called 'our lovely money' after the
signing of the Maastrict treaty on monetary and political union last autumn.
The minister's remarks reflect the sensitivity of Bonn political circles to
widespread disenchantment with the move towards a single currency, but fall
short of giving the people a referendum.
A poll conducted by Der Spiegel news magazine in the wake of the Danish vote
against the Maastrict treaty showed almost three quarters of Germans in the
western part of the country in favour of their own referendum on the issue,
and a majority against political union with a common currency.
In the same interview, Mr Waigel said there would be no new solidarity
surcharge tax to pay for the costs of reunification. However car drivers
would have to pay a toll by 1994 to help Bonn fund the reform of its
railways system and to keep its roads from becoming overburdened.
'To finance the restructuring of the railways we will introduce a levy on
autobahn use in the form of a vignette. That is the price that needs to be
paid to prevent a collapse of the road system,' Mr Waigel said.
A vignette is a sticker to be attached to the windscreen which would cost
the same for all car drivers. Mr Waigel did not say what price the vignette
would be.
The recent fall in the German inflation rate - from 4.3 per cent in June to
3.3 per cent in July - was no grounds for a cut in Germany's interest rates,
Mr Otmar Issing, the Bundesbank's chief economist and member of its
policy-making directorate, told the Welt am Sonntag yesterday.
It was essential to bring money supply growth down to the 3.5-5.5 per cent
growth target set by the Bundesbank , he said, and even a 3.3 per cent
inflation rate was not a level with which the central bank could feel happy.
The middle-term objective was to return to inflation 'with a 2 before the
comma', he said.
The Bundesbank's anti-inflation policy could not be held responsible for the
3m unemployed in Germany, nor was it likely to impede an upswing in eastern
Germany.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
