<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 92 / Foreign Exchanges and Money Markets: Waiting for M3
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GERMAN monetary policy will come under even closer scrutiny this week, as
the D-Mark threatens to make further gains against both the US dollar and
European currencies, writes James Blitz.
Last week's figure for German wholesale prices in July suggested that
inflationary pressures had eased, and slowed the D-Mark's gains against the
dollar. Dealers believe that falling German inflation will reduce the need
for the Bundesbank to keep interest rates high, reducing the wide
differential between US and German short-term rates that is driving the
market.
July's figure for M3 money supply in Germany, which is due out this week,
will help to confirm whether the pressure on rates has really eased. The
indicator is the guiding light of Bundesbank policy, and is expected to
reamain high, at around 8.6 per cent from a previous close of 8.7 per cent.
Some analysts think that the figure could even come in above 9 per cent,
ensuring tight monetary policy.
The markets will keep a close eye on the Bundesbank's weekly intervention in
the money market. Last week, the central bank triggered a fall in the dollar
by withdrawing more liquidity than was expected, pushing call money up to
the Lombard rate level. If the Bank adds net liquidity on Wednesday, the
D-Mark could weaken.
Inside the European Monetary System, the main attention will be on sterling.
Barring open intervention from the Bank of England, sterling's key indicator
will be the provisional figure for second quarter GDP, due out on Wednesday.
After a  1/2 per cent fall in the first quarter, the market believes that
the decline is slowing down to -0.2 per cent.
</TEXT>
