<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 92 / People: Home help Benyon
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
How would George Peabody have tackled the problems of London's homeless if
he had been alive today? This is a question that William Benyon, the former
Tory MP, will be increasingly asking himself as he takes up his new job in
January as chairman of the Peabody Trust, London's largest housing charity.
The problems of London's poor have changed considerably since George
Peabody, the one-time supposedly heartless American banker, suddenly
disarmed his many critics by setting up the Peabody Trust in 1862 with a
Pounds 500,000 donation. However, the trust, which houses 25,000 Londoners
on some 70 Peabody Estates, has not moved with the times as quickly as it
might.
A paternalistic organisation, for many years Peabody's main motivation
seemed to be to keep the rents on its properties as low as possible. To this
extent it has been very successful with average rents for two bedroom houses
ranging from Pounds 25 in Haringey to Pounds 48 in Ealing.
However, Benyon, who takes over his unpaid role from Hugh Astor, hopes that
Peabody can come to play a far bigger role in tackling poverty generally,
rather than just providing cheap housing. The problem is balancing the costs
of a Pounds 200m ten-year modernisation of Peabody's existing old properties
with wider plans to help the homeless and disadvantaged. He says that he has
a number of ideas but refuses to be drawn on them because 'negotiations are
very ticklish at the moment.'
*****
NATIONAL WESTMINSTER BANK has appointed a new boss of its operations in
London's West End a month after it sacked 185 staff. Andrew Blessley, 41,
has been appointed regional executive director for the bank's West End
region which puts him in charge of over 90 branches and more than 3200 staff
in the heart of London.
The bank says that there is no connection between Blessley's appointment and
the sackings, which have caused considerable ill-feeling amongst the bank
staff. Blessley's predecessor, Alan Thomas, 57, retired in May.
Nevertheless, whilst all big banks have been operating voluntary redundancy
schemes, NatWest has gone further than most by identifying the staff it
wants to get rid of, as opposed to those who want to leave voluntarily, and
summarily dismissing them. One of Blessley's first tasks will be to rebuild
staff morale which Richard Lynch, senior London organiser for the Banking
Insurance and Finance Union, says is at an all-time low.
Blessley, who joined the bank after reading modern languages at Cambridge,
has spent the bulk of his 20-year NatWest career on the international side.
He spent three years in San Francisco, was seconded to Banco Nacional in
Mexico City for six months, and worked in New York for several years. In
October 1990 he was appointed assistant general manager of the group chief
executive's office.
*****
Ron Williams, NatWest's director of business operations, UK branch business,
has been appointed ceo of EUROPAY INTERNATIONAL, the company created by the
merger between Eurocard International and eurocheque International.
*****
Hans-Dietrich Bauernfeind has been appointed a director of THORNTON ASIAN
EMERGING MARKETS INVESTMENT TRUST.
*****
Ted Lord, formerly head of financial engineering at Citibank Frankfurt, has
joined BZW Frankfurt as a director of corporate finance.
*****
Christine Shepherd, Julia Prescott, Rosamund Williams, Pavlos Stellakis,
Jonathan Trower, John Ross, Christine Cottrell, Jonathan Daniels, John
Davies, Mike Campion, Tom Murphy and Bruce Offergelt have been appointed to
the board of HILL SAMUEL BANK.
*****
Akis Karayiannis, formerly a vice-president at Citicorp, has joined LEHMAN
BROTHERS INTERNATIONAL as an executive director and head of foreign exchange
sales and trading in London.
*****
Usha Kelly has been appointed technical director in the personal financial
planning division of BAIN CLARKSON FINANCIAL SERVICES; Craig Stansfield is
promoted to regional director.
*****
John Pearce has been appointed a director of LONDON AMERICAN VENTURES TRUST.
*****
Marilyn Fee White has been appointed director of marketing, based in New
York, of Posthorn Global Asset Management, a London-based subsidiary of
SHEARSON LEHMAN BROTHERS.
