<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 92 / Looters seize part of relief shipment to Somalia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE and MICHAEL HOLMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOGADISHU
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RELIEF operations in famine-stricken southern Somalia were sabotaged
yesterday when armed looters seized part of the first United Nations
shipment of food and fuel into the port of Kismayo.
The need for UN military protection of relief operations was underlined when
local militia hired to protect the shipment stole 600 tonnes of food and
fuel.
The supplies were meant for an estimated 200,000 starving people in and
around the port, including 10,000 children believed by the UN to be in the
final throes of malnutrition. About 1.5m people are facing starvation in the
country.
The looting in Kismayo took place as rival gunmen shot dead three people in
the port of Mogadishu, disrupting efforts to unload food from two ships.
In spite of security problems, international relief efforts were boosted
yesterday by the news that the US would begin an airlift of 145,000 tonnes
of food to Somalia. But the news surprised aid officials in Mogadishu,
raising questions about the level of co-ordination between donors.
An Irish relief official aboard the ship in the port of Kismayo described
the scene in a radio call to UN headquarters in Mogadishu: 'The security
situation is critical. I can see them looting as I speak to you.'
In a tense but controlled radio conversation the official said the rest of
the shipment was effectively being held to ransom by Somali port officials
and gunmen, who were demanding Dollars 140,000 (Pounds 73,298) for customs
clearance, security and other claimed fees. This was Dollars 100,000 more
than the official had expected to pay.
Some Somali officials in Kismayo were said to be calculating their charges
at an exchange rate of Somali Shillings 5,800 to the dollar, instead of the
normal market rate of 7,400.
Mr Husein Yusuf of the Red Cross said at least 10,000 UN guards were needed
urgently to safeguard relief operations.
</TEXT>
