<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 92 / Briefcase, Q&amp;A: Pension has been overpaid
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
I HAVE been notified by my assurance society that they have overpaid my
pension annuity since commencement in 1988. Although they have said they
will not seek the return of the overpayment, can they reduce the pension
after issuing (and my acceptance of) the policy? They are asking for the
return of the policy document for amendment. Do you advise this?
As a matter of good insurance practice we consider that, where a mistake has
been made in your favour, of a modest amount, then a company should live
with this mistake and continue paying the annuity.
If the mistake is so large that it ought to have been apparent to the
trustees of the scheme or their professional advisers, or to you yourself if
you were the person who was shopping around in the annuity market, then the
solution they are proposing is reasonable.
You should not return the annuity policy as they request pending a fuller
investigation. The annuity market is highly competitive and rates often
change, even among the leading companies, on a weekly basis. It would be all
too easy for an insurance company to underquote its competitors, get the
business and then (as in your case) say: 'Sorry, we've made a mistake and
we're going to correct it.'
In other cases, the mistake might be genuine but the employee in the
insurance company who made it could be trying to cover his own tracks.
If, therefore, you judge that you are being overpaid by only a modest
percentage, then we suggest that you write to the chief executive at the
head office of the insurance company in question, making the points set out
in this reply. If that fails to produce a satisfactory result, you should
write to the insurance ombudsman: Dr Julian Farrand, City Gate One, 135 Park
Street, London SE1 9EA.
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All inquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
