<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 92 / Finance &amp; The Family: No fun for fund of funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A 'FUND of funds' sounds like the ideal unit trust for the first-time equity
investor.
The average investor is probably bewildered by all the different categories
of unit trust - from UK growth to Australasia, from Japan to international
growth. A 'fund of funds' allows the investor to leave that decision to the
professionals, who select the best trusts from a company's stable in order
to create a nicely diversified portfolio.
However, what sounds good in theory has not worked so well in practice. Not
one of the trusts in the sector has delivered a positive return to investors
over either three or five years. The average 'fund of funds' has delivered a
loss to its unitholders, even with reinvested income, over one, two, three
and five years.
Now Midland Bank has revealed plans to reorganise its Managed Portfolio
trust, the biggest in the sector. Instead of investing in unit trusts the
revamped fund, renamed Midland Balanced, will buy equities directly. As a
consequence, it will be classed in the international balanced sector, rather
than in 'funds of funds'.
So what has gone wrong with the fund of funds concept? The main problem has
been the depressed state of the world's stock markets. Five years ago, in
the summer of 1987, shares were trading at then record levels, in the
expectation of years of continued economic growth. Then came the crash of
October 1987. In the UK, the main share indices are still no higher than
they were five years ago; in Japan, they are considerably lower.
There are few unit trust sectors which can show even half-way decent
performance figures over five years. Just six sectors can boast that an
average trust earned the investor a profit, and in two of those cases, Japan
and north America, the overall return has been under 10 per cent. The best
sector has been gilt &amp; fixed interest, where the average investor has
returned 32.4 per cent over the five years to August 1.
Managers of 'funds of funds' therefore have had the odds stacked against
them.
The only way they could have avoided a loss was by concentrating on a
limited number of sectors. But many managers cannot do so - Lloyds Bank
Mastertrust, for example, is required to hold at least 60 per cent of its
portfolio in UK equities.
Difficulties can also arise from the rule which prevents a 'fund of funds'
from investing more than 20 per cent of its assets in an individual trust.
This limits the manager's options, particularly if, say, he feels that gilts
are going to outperform equities.
Poor performance aside, there is another problem - the scope for double
charging. In some cases, the investor pays an annual management charge to
the 'fund of funds' manager, who in turn is buying units in trusts where a
further annual charge is levied.
At least the investor does not have to pay the manager's initial charge
twice. The 'fund of funds' manager can normally buy units at the creation
price, which is essentially the bid price plus the manager's cost in buying
and selling shares (the market maker's spread, commission etc).
There are 43 'funds of funds' in the sector with a total of about Pounds
770m under management on August 1. The revamp of Midland's Managed
Portfolio, which had Pounds 272.9m under management, will reduce the sector
by over a third.
The size of Midland's fund's increased greatly in 1988, when the group
launched unit trust personal pension plans. Most pension investors like the
implied security and stability of a managed fund. But the result was that
the Midland managed portfolio became the biggest single investor in many of
the bank's unit trusts. If the managed fund then wanted to sell its holding,
that caused terrible problems for the other unit trust managers.
Under Midland's plan, the new Balanced trust will be established and
holdings in Managed Portfolio will be transferred into it (subject, of
course, to unitholders' agreement).
Midland will also take the opportunity to streamline its unit trust range,
with five other trusts (Meridian Growth, Meridian Income, International High
Street, Capital and Smaller Companies) also being absorbed by the Balanced
fund.
Midland says the new Balanced fund will have greater flexibility than before
and expects it to be the flagship of its unit trust range.
Investors will certainly be hoping that the new structure will produce
better performance than the old - Midland Managed Portfolio was bottom of
its sector over three and five years.
