<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 92 / Finance &amp; The Family: Interest blitz by Revenue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AJ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NON-TAXPAYERS who have registered to receive their interest gross from banks
and building societies should ensure that their income does not exceed their
personal allowances.
The Inland Revenue expressed concern this week that a significant number of
people who have registered are, in fact, taxpayers and will have to revert
to receiving interest net of tax.
Since the gross interest scheme was introduced in April, an estimated 15m
accounts - representing about 7m people - have been registered. To be
eligible, their total income must be less than their personal allowances.
But recent research by the Revenue suggests that up to 1m of these people
actually are taxpayers and should be receiving interest net.
The Revenue is stressing that most who have registered probably have
misunderstood the regulations and have not attempted to defraud its
inspectors. These include:
Pensioners who may have forgotten to include their retirement pensions as
part of their income.
People with several savings accounts who may have thought they could
register to receive gross interest on one account if they had allowances to
cover the interest on it.
The Revenue has begun an 'audit' of people registered to receive interest
gross. It will approach either them or their tax offices for information and
will ask banks and building societies to start paying interest net on any
accounts found to belong to taxpayers. It could also ask for tax owing.
If it finds that someone has made false declarations deliberately and
knowingly, it will also considering levying interest on the tax, fines of up
to Pounds 3,000, and penalties up to the value of the tax not paid.
Anyone who believes they have registered wrongly should notify their tax
office or write to Colin Gillbanks, Inland Revenue Claims Branch, Savings &amp;
Investments (BRT), St John's House, Merton Road, Bootle, Merseyside L69 9BB.
Non-taxpayers registering to receive interest gross should complete form
R85. Details are provided in leaflet IR 110.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
