<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 92 / Letter: UN need for a disaster relief office
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr JOHN SAUNDERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Julian Ozanne writes (Personal View, August 10) that 'for several years
there has been a suggestion that a well-funded disaster relief office be set
up at the UN.' As a consultant to the secretary-general in 1987 I made such
a proposal, intended as a first step in the establishment of a permanent,
powerful body, under the authority of the secretary-general, to lead the
world's action on disasters. I made other suggestions on how the UN could be
ahead of emergencies, as far as possible, abandoning the method of ad hoc
response after the event which had been standard procedure, and sadly still
is.
My proposal was hardly novel, being based on the UN experience of
humanitarian operations, gained over many years, and not least through my
friend, the late Sir Robert Jackson, probably the greatest leader in
humanitarian emergencies the UN, and indeed the world, has ever had. There
were also the remarkable achievements of Maurice Strong and Bradford Morse,
organisers of the widely acclaimed UN office for emergency operations in
Africa. The secretary-general did not adopt my main recommendations, no
doubt because he considered that the member governments were not ready to
face up to the implications for international organisations.
Julian Ozanne's many other proposals have already been put forward by
experts over the years. The actions required have long been understood. What
we do not have are decisions, which must be by member governments through
the UN. If governments will not act, the secretary-general can try to
persuade.
An ironic footnote to Mr Ozanne's main suggestion is that the new
secretary-general did indeed appoint a disaster relief co-ordinator, Mr Jan
Eliasson, on March 1 this year, as part of the re-organisation of the UN.
Given the problem I describe, Mr Eliasson has hardly been heard from, not
surprisingly since he will not have had an opportunity to play a significant
role in the terrible problem of Somalia.
John Saunders,
(former special representative of the secretary-general in Lebanon, and of
Unicef in Kampuchea),
20 Shirleys,
Ditchling, Hassocks,
West Sussex BN6 8UD
</TEXT>
