<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 92 / Letter: Suffering of Olympic athletes - ancient and modern
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr STEPHEN INSTONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I wonder if the modern Olympics are in essence so very different from
the ancient Olympics. Nicholas Woodsworth has twice suggested that they are,
most recently in his piece 'Marathon a sell-out to commercialism' (August
8), where he suggests that the suffering of the marathon runners at
Barcelona was alien to the ideals of Olympic competition.
It is not immediately clear whose ideals, or what ideals, he is referring
to, but there is plenty of evidence to suggest that ancient Greek athletes
suffered just as much, perhaps more, than modern ones, and that the idea
that the modern Olympics are a corrupt departure from some higher ancient
standard is unfounded.
Pausanias (2nd century AD) tells the following story about Arrachion, a
competitor in the ancient Greek Olympics in the pankration (a brutal mixture
of boxing, wrestling, and general fighting, in which gouging the eyes and
biting were forbidden but anything else allowed):
'Arrachion's opponent caught him, held him in a scissors grip and at the
same time throttled him with his hands; so Arrachion broke one of the man's
toes. Arra chion died by strangling, but not before the strangler gave in
from the pain in his toe.'
Arrachion was the winner - but dead.
The idea that ancient athletes did not have financial motives is also
questionable. The Athenian statesman Solon (probably early 6th century)
awarded Athenian victors in the Olympics 500 drachmas; it is difficult to
evaluate this sum, but rape was punished by a fine of 100 drachmas and five
drachmas were awarded to anyone who brought into the city a wolf.
Stephen Instone,
6 Queen's Road,
London SW14 8PJ
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 7
</PAGE>
</DOC>
