<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 92 / Battle for Salzburg's soul: A more modern festival is
emerging
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW CLARK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
You can still pay up to Dollars 350 (Pounds 183) for an opera performance in
Salzburg this summer, but the choice may be Janacek or Messiaen rather than
Mozart and Strauss. You can still dress in black tie or put on your
favourite tiara, but don't be surprised to find scruffy students and
tourists in the same block of seats.
Salzburg is undergoing an identity crisis. Gone is the extravagant
conservatism of the past quarter-century, when Herbert von Karajan - the
conductor and Salzburg's most famous son after Mozart - presided over its
world-renowned festival.
In its place comes a bolder, more contemporary creed preached by Gerard
Mortier, a loquacious, idealistic Belgian who - as incoming artistic
director - wants to transform the festival's character and bring in a new
public. You can already sense the difference: the atmosphere is less formal,
the audience looks younger. There are fewer stars than before and more empty
seats.
No one doubted the need for change. Critics and commentators believed the
festival had become too elitist and money-oriented. But Salzburg has got
more than it bargained for. Mortier, who made his name with adventurous
opera programming in Brussels, has introduced new and unfamiliar works - to
which Salzburg's traditional audiences have proved resistant. He has engaged
stage directors like Peter Sellars and the Herrmanns, whose radical style is
anathema to the festival's older supporters. He has laid particular emphasis
on the younger generation, awarding the prestigious opening concert to the
Gustav Mahler Youth Orchestra and handing out tickets to students for as
little as Dollars 9.
Mortier couches his programme in lofty philosophical terms, proclaiming
Salzburg as a 'utopia of the new Europe', a cradle of aesthetic
internationalism - a far cry from the pure Germanic tradition on which the
festival once thrived.
Coming from an outsider, this kind of talk makes locals nervous. For much of
the year Salzburg is little more than a quiet, provincial, Austrian town. In
the postwar era it prospered from the festival's up-market status and its
ability to attract swarms of summer visitors. It is suspicious of anyone
trying to graft an alien personality on to its contented Austrian face.
Many festival-goers are prepared to allow Mortier a honeymoon, and some of
his innovations have been enthusiastically received. The appointment of
Peter Stein as drama director, for example, allowed spoken theatre to resume
the central role it had when Hugo von Hofmannsthal and Max Reinhardt founded
the festival in the 1920s. Stein's production of Shakespeare's Julius Caesar
was the popular hit of the opening week this summer, and there will be a
wider selection of drama next year.
Mortier's contemporary music programme is another welcome contrast to the
Karajan years, when living composers received little more than a token nod.
And Salzburg is at last able to hear the baroque and classical repertoire in
state-of-the-art performances by Nikolaus Harnoncourt, William Christie and
other period-instrument specialists. Harnoncourt, an
internationally-renowned Austrian whom Karajan excluded from the festival,
made his debut two weeks ago with a revelatory Missa Solemnis, and will
conduct a Monteverdi opera next year.
Despite these gains - and the continued presence of Solti, Abbado and other
leading conductors - there is a strong undercurrent of resistance to the new
regime. What irks Mortier's opponents is not just the substance of his
programme - the feeling that he is trying to do too much too soon - but also
his outspoken style.
In a series of press interviews, he has trodden on local sensibilities and
alienated sections of the music industry. He accused the major record
companies of using 'mafia tactics' to influence casting during the Karajan
era, and spoke of 'evil people' who exploited their relationship with the
conductor to his dying day. The Karajan estate promptly threatened legal
action, and the mayor of Salzburg called an emergency meeting of the
festival's supervisory body, saying Mortier's statements could cause
irreparable damage.
Mortier has also had a run-in with the local business community. Reacting to
claims that his programme had caused a drop in trade, he told Salzburg's
shopkeepers and hoteliers it was time they started doing something for the
festival 'instead of always milking it'. He also lectured councillors on how
to make better year-round use of Salzburg's facilities, and called on the
city to co-operate with Brussels-based cultural programmes promoted by the
European Community.
Mortier cannot afford to alienate too many people. Ten days before the start
of the festival, Riccardo Muti stormed out of a new production of Mozart's
La clemenza di Tito, claiming the staging by Karl-Ernst and Ursel Herrmann
was an offence to Mozart's music. Although Muti was by no means blameless,
the Tito fracas has been billed as a struggle between the old and the new at
Salzburg. The Italian star conductor has been a festival favourite since
1971: he owns a house in the community where Karajan lived, and talks of the
need to respect festival traditions established by great conductors of the
past.
Muti's supporters include the Vienna Philharmonic, one of the festival's
main power-brokers and a guarantor of its musical standards. So far the
orchestra has co-operated with Mortier, but it has voiced misgivings about
the quality of some guest orchestras he has invited.
Sponsors must also be kept happy: Mortier has signed a five-year agreement
with Nestle, Asea Brown-Boveri and Allianz, who will provide Dollars 2m each
year. And the festival's Friends Organisation must be restocked, after the
defection of rich Karajan loyalists.
Several of the most important events of Mortier's opening season take place
in the final two weeks, beginning tonight with the first of six Boulez
concerts. Monday sees the premiere of Sellars' staging of Messiaen's Saint
Francois d'Assise. Modern interpretations of Strauss and Mozart operas
follow later in the week.
Mortier is hoping these will provide a popular mandate for change and
silence his conservative critics. A battle for the soul of the festival is
under way.
</TEXT>
