FT  15 AUG 92 / Police pay board calls for 6.5% rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POLICE OFFICERS' pay is likely to rise by 6.5 per cent this year even though
average earnings, which determine police pay, have risen by less than that.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, home secretary, will shortly consider the recommendations
of the Police Negotiating Board for a 6.5 per cent rise amid growing
pressure for the government to restrain public-sector earnings. If he wanted
to take a hard line he could press for the rise to be restricted to 6.25 per
cent - saving about Pounds 10m - without breaking the government's pledge to
link police pay to average earnings increases.
The Department of Employment last week revised the average earnings figure
for the year to May - the period which determines police officers' rises -
to 6.25 per cent from the 6.5 per cent reported previously.
A decision to make the rise 6.25 per cent would signal the government's
determination to tighten its grip on public pay but it would infuriate the
129,000 police officers who already feel insecure because of a government
inquiry into their pay and conditions.
The negotiating board made its recommendation of a 6.5 per cent rise before
last week's revision of the earnings figure. Members said yesterday they
would be surprised if their recommendation were overturned.
</TEXT>
