<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 92 / Georgia rebels free minister as fighting flares
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
DISSIDENTS in the former Soviet republic of Georgia freed a government
minister and most other hostages yesterday, as troops and police clamped
down on their rebellious region, agencies report from Tbilisi.
Mr Roman Gventsadze, the interior minister, who was seized on Tuesday along
with 11 police officials, returned to Tbilisi by helicopter late last night,
looking pale and tired.
He said his captors released him because they were afraid of the big force
being deployed against them yesterday.
The Georgian government based in Tbilisi sent more than 3,000 national
guardsmen and more than 400 police to seal off the rebellious Abkhazia
region in the west of the republic to prevent the hostages being spirited
further away. The hostages were reportedly held in a village 170 miles from
Tbilisi.
The guardsmen blocked bridges, roads and railways throughout Abkhazia, at
times running into resistance.
The sharpest flare-up of fighting came as they swept into the Black Sea
resort of Sukhumi, the regional capital. National Guard helicopters were
reported to have opened fire on Abkhazian forces near the region's
parliament building, and rockets destroyed a runway at Sukhumi airport.
At least 10 people were killed, according to an Abkhazian official, although
other reports spoke of three dead and many wounded.
Abkhazia declared independence from Georgia last month, angering hardliners
in Georgia's provisional government, which is led by Mr Eduard Shevardnadze,
the former Soviet foreign minister
The hostage-taking has presented Mr Shevardnadze with his most serious
crisis since returning to his native Georgia in March as political leader.
Mr Shevardnadze said the 'bandits' were still holding Mr Alexander Kavsadze,
a deputy prime minister taken hostage several weeks ago, and two police
officials. He said the militants at one stage promised to free all hostages
yesterday but changed their minds after talking by phone to Mr Gamsakhurdia,
who has taken refuge in Russia.
Abkhazian leaders apparently did not organise the hostage-taking or have
direct control over the hostages. But the hostage crisis has turned into a
larger political dispute.
Abkhazia's parliament ordered a general mobilisation of citizens to resist
the troops.
</TEXT>
