<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 92 / International Company News: Citicorp restates latest results
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US BANKING group Citicorp revealed last night that it has restated its
previously announced second-quarter results from a profit of Dollars 171m to
a profit of Dollars 143m in the wake of an examination of the US mortgage
business by bank regulators that was completed after Citicorp filed its
second-quarter earnings.
Citicorp also confirmed yesterday that it signed an informal memorandum of
understanding with federal regulators earlier this year agreeing to keep
regulators more closely informed of moves by the bank to strengthen its
capital position.
On the issue of its restatement of earnings, Citicorp said that although its
management and its independent auditors had agreed that the original
second-quarter earnings report was consistent with Generally Accepted
Accounting Principles, net income had to be adjusted by Dollars 28m to
reflect the regulators' different judgment on the level of future repayments
of mortgages.
The bank admitted, however, that because of the recent change in interest
rate expectations, it would have taken an identical charge against
third-quarter earnings even with its existing approach to mortgage
valuation.
In a separate accounting move, Citicorp said that it had also changed the
balance sheet classification of Dollars 149m of mortgage properties. The
classification was switched from 'delinquent consumer mortgages' to 'other
real estate owned' to reflect circumstances where the borrower has
effectively relinquished control over the property although foreclose has
not occurred.
The net effect of the change, which Citicorp said had no impact on earnings
because of previously established reserves, has reduced consumer loans at
June 30, 1992 from Dollars 89.5bn to Dollars 89.3bn.
The Student Loan Marketing Association revealed yesterday that it has made a
preliminary offer to acquire the Dollars 2.5bn of guaranteed student loans
owned by Citibank.
</TEXT>
