<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 92 / Dieppe, a disaster beyond words: Fifty years ago this week,
20 journalists were allowed to accompany the Allied raid: one of the first
big propaganda exercises of modern warfare. What they, in fact, saw was a
tragic and costly fiasco
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SUZANNE BARDGETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD LOVAT, commanding officer of No. 4 Commando, was in expansive mood as
he talked to his men on the eve of the Dieppe raid. 'They tell me the
propaganda's terrific,' he told them. 'All our families will be glued to
their radio sets when they hear the BBC announcement tomorrow morning.'
Among the many preparations discussed at the London headquarters of Combined
Operations in the early months of 1942, publicity had indeed been a
prominent issue. The war was not going well for the Allies. The year had
begun with the fall of Singapore; troops in the Western Desert had suffered
a series of reverses; Hitler's armies were advancing across the Soviet
Union. A successful raid on the French Channel port was a chance to boost
morale at home and reassure Britain's hard-pressed Russian and American
allies.
Public relations was a new-fangled notion, foreign to the training and
temperament of most senior British officers. But at Combined Operations'
headquarters, Lord Mountbatten's youthful and eager PR team  - which
included several ex-Hollyood professionals - took a more opportunistic view.
COHQ's brief - to mount raids on occupied territories - clearly offered
tremendous scope for action stories.
Cameramen and reporters had accompanied raids on the occupied Lofoten
Islands and Vaagso, in Norway, with gratifying results. The film record of
Vaagso, in particular, with its shots of flaming factories and commandos
creeping across snow-covered terrain, was convincing proof of the propaganda
value of allowing the media into the front line. Hopes were, therefore, high
for Dieppe - far more ambitious and code-named 'Operation Rutter.'
The plan involved an attack by a force of 6,000, largely Canadian, on a
10-mile front of the French coast. Flanking raids on the villages on either
side of the port would be followed by an attack on Dieppe itself, after
which troops would move inland to attack the Luftwaffe fighter base at St
Aubin and the divisional headquarters at Arques la Bataille. The whole
enterprise would be supported by naval destroyers and squadrons of the RAF.
It would be the greatest amphibious operation since Gallipoli and the first
time in history that tanks would be landed on beaches in the face of enemy
opposition. Dazzled by the opportunities that such an operation would surely
bring, and blind to the possibility that it could fail, Mountbatten's
publicity officers set about making Dieppe the greatest story of the war.
The press men covering the enterprise needed to be physically fit and, in
the spring of 1942, a hand-picked few were given a taste of assault warfare.
The Daily Herald's Sandy Austin found himself despatched to a remote part of
Scotland where a new type of flat-bottomed tank landing craft was being
plunged in and out of lochs. Then, late in June, six reporters were shipped
to the Isle of Wight where they joined a big Canadian force rehearsing the
raid on the island's cliff-rimmed coastline. Anticipation was running high;
however, bad weather gave the planners doubts and, on July 7, what was to
have been Operation Rutter was cancelled. But at the end of July, the raid
was revived under the code-name 'Jubilee' and scheduled for the night of
August 18-19.
Confidence must have been high, for the re-assembled press party had now
swollen to 20. Secrecy was crucial and, to ensure that no word got out,
COHQ's public relations officers played out an elaborate ruse, transporting
the entire press team to Bristol where it was put up in hotels and told to
have no communications with third parties. Two days later, a canopied army
truck appeared and the journalists were taken on a lengthy cross-country
journey, arriving eventually at Newhaven, East Sussex. These efforts at
subterfuge were admirable but a touch superfluous: at least three of the
party - Austin, Frank Gillard and John McVane - had been given full
briefings on the plan the previous month.
On the night of Tuesday August 18, more than 200 ships carrying nearly 6,000
troops set out under pale moonlight. The sea was calm and, for several
hours, the only sound came from the throb of propellers and the sloshing of
water against hulls. But as the vessels neared the French coast, there was a
sudden burst of light, with golden and red sprays criss-crossing the sky.
No. 3 Commando had run into a patrol of German E-boats. For 20 minutes the
raiders watched the spectacle, unaware that it was the first and most
serious of the mishaps that would turn the whole show into a disaster.
The first landings took place just before dawn. First ashore of the press
men was Austin with No. 4 Commando. Machine-gun fire sounded from the
cliff-top, but the commandos blew up the barbed-wire defences and made their
way up a gully that led to a great howitzer battery at Varengeville. Later
that morning, Austin was pressed into service with the troops, helping to
carry messages and mortar shells up the gully. Eventually, he conveyed the
triumphant news: 'Battery demolished. 6.50.'
A couple of miles closer to the port, Wallace Reyburn, a 29-year-old
reporter for the Montreal Standard, landed with the South Saskatchewans at
Pourville. With him were two members of the army film and photographic unit,
Lieutenant WT Lockeyear and Sergeant Ron Holloway, the latter only recently
recruited and on his first assignment. At first, all went well. A number of
German prisoners was rounded up. Then, mortar shells appeared from nowhere
and Reyburn found himself heaving wounded Canadians on to stretchers.
The troops advanced towards Dieppe but were met with ever-fiercer shelling,
and Reyburn lost track of his photographer companions. (It emerged later
that Holloway had been wounded in the eye but carried on recording the
battle, only to be hit again, this time fatally - the only press man at
Dieppe who did not return).
Reyburn found a house where, for several hours, he was able to watch the
fighting. Eventually, a wireless message was sent requesting that the
landing craft come and take the raiders off. With Nazi troops advancing
towards the town it was, as Reyburn reported, 'a toss-up who reached us
first.' When the boats finally arrived at 11.00, Reyburn witnessed one of
the most harrowing episodes of the raid as 800 troops raced from the cover
of the sea wall - only to be mown down by machine-gun fire. Reyburn had
spent nearly six hours ashore.
To the east of Dieppe, Canadian Press reporter Ross Munro accompanied the
Royal Regiment of Canada to Puits, code-named Blue Beach. A 15-minute delay
lost the raiders the cover of darkness and, in haste to make up for lost
time, the landing craft engines were revved at full speed, alerting the
shore defences.
Munro wrote: 'Down went the ramp and out poured the first infantrymen. They
plunged into about two feet of water and machine-gun fire laced into them.'
Munro later was stunned to realise that, of the 80 men in his craft, only 20
had re-boarded. 'On no other front have I witnessed such a carnage,' he
wrote in 1946. 'It was brutal and terrible and shocked you almost to
insensibility.'
Some miles out to sea, Quentin Reynolds was the first of the press party to
appreciate how far things had gone wrong. A personal friend of two of
Mountbatten's staff officers, he had sailed on the headquarters ship Calpe,
where he had direct access to General Roberts, commander of the Canadian
Second Division. In Roberts' control cabin, he now heard the commmander's
urgent wireless message: 'Calling Red Beach. Calling Red Beach. Calling Blue
Beach.' Seemingly hours later, a faint crackle came back: 'Red Beach
calling. We are being strafed by Focke-Wulfs. Situation serious.' From Blue
Beach, there was silence. The headquarters signaller had been killed and his
transmitter smashed by bullets.
For the 14 press men hovering in boats offshore, events could only be
guessed at from the gruesome evidence that now and then floated into view.
Landing craft emerged from under the smoke-screen, half-filled with men -
some dead, some dying, the water lapping red around their bodies.
From those able to speak came dazed accounts of the past few hours: 'The
bloody Jerries were waiting for us.' 'We had to land in daylight.'
'Machine-guns at 50 yards, and the place lousy with mines and mortars.' A
pale lieutenant, asked how things were going ashore, could only repeat: 'You
may well ask.'
Back in London, with news now arriving from the Calpe, Mountbatten's
publicity team faced a crisis of mounting proportions. A communique issued
at 06.00 that day had produced its intended effect of galvanising the
nation's news desks, and telephones were ringing incessantly. To which ports
would the soldiers be returning? Could reporters be sent to interview them?
With furrowed brows, the officers turned to the second communique, drafted
in advance but now patently in need of revision. There was a hasty telephone
call to Mountbatten at RAF Uxbridge, in north-west London. A confidential
note to editors warned: 'Losses must be seen in the light of valuable
experience gained.'
For a full seven hours, the sky over Dieppe shook with the roar of the air
battle. In the Calpe's wardroom, two doctors tried to save the wounded,
dealing eventually with 500 men. At one point, the bedraggled figure of
Reyburn appeared. 'This is one hell of a story,' he gasped at Reynolds. Then
he passed out.
Around midnight, the returning ships reached the south coast ports. The
press men drove to their London offices, typed their reports and then sped
over to Combined Operations headquarters where a press conference had been
arranged for 10.00. The briefing was on the fourth floor. 'It was a long way
up,' recalled Reynolds, 'especially for Wally, whose wounds were smarting
now.' Mountbatten's expression gave nothing away. His spokesman gave a
carefully-worded summary: there had been some casualties but they had no
particulars yet. It was true that not all the raid's objectives had been
achieved, but the main purpose had been accomplished: 'We sent a large naval
force to Dieppe, kept them there for more than nine hours and suffered the
loss of only one destroyer.'
The reporters went away and tried to incorporate the official view into
their stories, although it was scarcely compatible with what they had seen
and heard. The rest of the day was spent wrangling with the four sets of
censors - COHQ's and the three services' - until a version of each
reporter's account could be agreed.
Overall, the balance sheet read badly. The pictures taken by Holloway in the
heat of the fighting in Pourville were lost. The much hoped-for film
coverage was derisory: the British Movietone News cameraman had been aboard
No. 3 Commando's leading gunboat, and his film amounted to little more than
shots of the damaged boat and wounded crew. But things could have been
worse. By a stroke of luck, the only British newspaperman to land in France
had seen the one phase of the raid that had gone according to plan. With a
clear conscience, Austin was able to file a gritty story about No. 4
Commando's storming of Varengeville battery, and it was this - to the
censors' relief - that was blazoned across every paper's front page when the
story finally reached the news-stands on Friday morning.
As the weeks passed, however, word got about that all had not been well at
Dieppe. There had been faults in the planning - inadequate intelligence and
a serious miscalculation of German strength - while poor communications, bad
luck and bad timing had let the operation down. 'Was it all worthwhile?' was
the question asked by many.
Within months, three of the reporters present wrote books about it -
accounts which, although they gave more details than the first reports,
remained faithful to the line that the raid was justified by the lessons it
had taught. It was hardly the action of dogged seekers-after-truth who,
having discharged their distasteful duty in reporting the raid to the
authorities' satisfaction, might have been expected, thankfully, to lay the
subject to rest. To be fair, the number of deaths had not at that time been
released, so that the raid had not acquired the tragic aura it has today;
but it is still surprising that Reyburn, who had seen the very worst of the
mayhem on Pourville beach, could open his book with an earnest and reasoned
defence of the official line.
The fact is that those reporters given access to front-line units did so
accepting that they were part of the propaganda arm. The three weeks of
training for Operation Rutter had produced among the press an admiration for
the raiding force that was close to awe. To have responded with carping
criticism would have been to jeopardise future opportunities. The reporters'
acquiescence earned trust and privileges that were crucial if the public was
to be given anything more than reports drawn on official communiques. By
entering this accord, though, the media lost their objectivity - perhaps an
inevitable consequence of war.
At the end of the day - as one of their number, author John Steinbeck, put
it - the correspondents of the Second World War were a 'curious, crazy, yet
responsible crew.' For the sake of the war effort, and because the war
against Hitler was considered a just one, they did what was required of
them. Dieppe - where nearly 1,000 men were killed and 2,000 taken prisoner -
showed how well the system worked.
Suzanne Bardgett is a special assistant on the directing staff of the
Imperial War Museum, London.
</TEXT>
