<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 92 / The Long View: Meeting the history man
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE familiar tones of Steve the strategist came on the line this week. 'Just
passing through,' he said. 'I thought I needed to get an update on the
latest ERM tensions. Looks like the rest of the year could be all about
currencies.'
When we met, it turned out that Steve, as a leading global investment guru,
was busy gathering material for the autumn conference season. He showed me
his diary for September and October, and I decided airline and luxury hotel
stocks should go on the buy list for a start.
'Client calls drop right away in August,' he said. 'Time for a bit of
longer-term thinking or, at least, a bit of longer-term re-formatting.' This
was a new phrase to me. I thought that format was a button on my computer
that I didn't know how to use. Presumably, though, it was all part of the
idea that presentation beats content any day.
'Why do journalists get so cynical?' complained Steve. 'Still, it's true
enough that there are very few good new ideas - just a better supply of new
ways to package old ones. Right now, the clients are into history. They want
1992 put into the context of the 1920s and the 1930s, or maybe even the
1890s if you want to be fancy.
'Personally, I think history is junk, certainly for predicting the stock
market. But if the clients expect me to have mugged up on Keynes and
Schumpeter and Galbraith, then at least I need to have skimmed through the
executive summaries. And when the clients want everything formatted in terms
of supercycles, they get it.'
You can become cynical through talking to global strategists, I thought. Out
loud, I said that the clients just might have something. The markets didn't
seem to be following the rules or the trend lines that they had for 20 or 30
years. For instance - in the UK, at any rate - analytical devices like
bond-equity yield ratios were outside their normal ranges, so strategists
who called the market cheap when the ratio hit the normal 2.0 floor were
looking exposed now it was down to under 1.8.
'Sure, I've looked at the UK numbers and the dividends are looking exposed,'
Steve agreed. 'Dividends have stalled in the past year. But in the five
years before then, they rose 90 per cent, or call it 40 per cent in real
terms. But the British economy is now only 10 per cent bigger than it was in
1985, and might still be shrinking. Those are the relationships to look at.'
Did he think it was worthwhile skimming through the history books to gain
insights into this kind of problem? Surely it was fair enough to look at
some longer-term data for a better perspective?
'Maybe,' said Steve, 'but you can't make money by doing in 1992 what you
should have done in 1932. Look how the Wall Street crash of 1987 was
misinterpreted. On the 1929 precedent, the Dow should have collapsed to
about 350. Instead it's gone 10 times as high. To me, there's only one way
of getting it right in any era and that's to look at what's cheap and what's
expensive and feed off the market's illusions.'
I said that the expensive junk often seemed to be the kind of stock peddled
by his firm's new-issue salesmen. 'Sure,' he said, 'you have to sell into
strength. The corporate clients have a surprisingly good feel for when their
stock is overvalued.
'There is valuable feedback for me, too. Of course, I have to be careful
what I say to clients. But look at what has happened in health care, which
soared out of sight last year when investors were desperate for
recession-proof earnings. New stock by the billion has poured out, including
Wellcome. I see that even ICI is trying to do the splits and dress half of
itself up as a fancy bio stock. You can bet it will miss the boat and the
dull old heavy chemicals rump will outperform.'
But switching between growth stocks and cyclicals had proved a tricky game
over the past year, I remarked. Small company stocks, which were among the
most sensitive to economic recovery, had been having a rough time.
'It's my longer-term play,' said Steve. 'Remember that Japan has lost the
zero cost of capital that allowed it to undermine returns on capital in
tradeable manufactures worldwide during the 1980s. Stands to reason that
manufacturing in the US and Europe will gain competitiveness through the
1990s. But don't hold your breath.'
He added: 'What worries me now is currencies. I was right to go short of the
dollar earlier in the year, but US interest rates have nowhere much lower to
go. Meanwhile, in Europe the pressure from cheap, dollar-based goods is
threatening to bust the ERM apart. Assuming the Italians go down, who will
they take with them?'
Just suppose, I said, that the French say 'non' to the Maastricht treaty on
September 20 and the Bundesbank puts up the Lombard Rate. Then, Bill Clinton
could win the US election. At least the winner won't be Ross Perot in a
three-way split, but the financial markets would not be at all happy. And we
should remember that US Treasury bonds yield less than German bunds. Was
that the real order of credit quality?
'You're right to worry. Everybody's worrying,' said Steve. 'But I have to
look at it the other way around. What if none of those things happens? A lot
of the risk is fully priced into the markets now. Suppose Bush wins -
remember, your John Major was a no-hoper before April, according to the
opinion polls - and suppose German short-term rates come down before
Christmas. Imagine what that might do to the dollar, and then the heat would
be right off the ERM. On that scenario, I might even buy the UK stock
market.'
</TEXT>
