<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 92 / International Company News: ING rejects 5% stake in BBL
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AMSTERDAM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONALE Nederlanden Group (ING), the Dutch banking and insurance
company, turned down a chance to buy a 5 per cent stake in Belgium's
second-largest bank, Banque Bruxelles Lambert, but reaffirmed its interest
in raising its 10 per cent stake.
ING is eager to create a second 'home' market in Belgium but yesterday
rejected an offer from SBH Investment, a subsidiary of Unipar, the Italian
holding company, to acquire its nearly 914,000 shares in BBL at BFr3,800
(Dollars 125) each, about 10 per cent above their current market value.
BBL's major institutional shareholders belong to a syndicate which
stipulates that members must offer each other the right to first refusal
when divesting their holdings.
BBL said 'no shareholder in the syndicate decided to buy the shares at the
price fixed by SBH Investments'.
This leaves the Italian company free to find other buyers for the shares,
provided they are sold at BFr 3,800 each.
If it lowers the price, it must approach syndicate members again, starting
with Groupe Bruxelles Lambert (GBL) which owns a 13.5 per cent stake, but
which controls 24.2 per cent thanks to allies Royale Belge and UAP of
France.
ING said its decision was based on a 'complex of factors' but declined to
elaborate.
Analysts believe one factor is a Belgian law requiring that a public bid be
launched if an investor buys shares at a premium and thereby acquires
control of the company.
The 5.2 per cent holding would have formally made ING the single biggest
shareholder in BBL at 15.2 per cent, ahead of GBL. ING is seeking to
conclude an insurance partnership with BBL as part of its European expansion
plans, but GBL and some other Belgian institutions would prefer the bank to
forge links with the publicly-owned Belgian credit institution Credit
Communal.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
