<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 92 / International Company News: LTV bankruptcy moves step closer
to resolution
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE OF the most complex and fractious US bankruptcies moved a step closer to
resolution, after a Manhattan judge gave LTV Corporation, the large steel
company, permission to sell its missile and aircraft divisions for Dollars
475m late on Thursday.
The buyer of the LTV businesses is a group comprising Loral Corporation,
Northrop and Carlyle Group, an investment banking firm. Loral will take over
the missile unit for Dollars 261m and Northrop/Carlyle will buy the aircraft
operations for Dollars 214m.
This bid, of which Dollars 450m is in cash and Dollars 25m in preferred
stock, topped a Dollars 440m rival offer from Martin Marietta.
Under the terms, the Loral group could be liable for a Dollars 100m payment
if it fails to close the transaction, while Martin Marietta gets a Dollars
5m fee, in return for releasing LTV from its earlier pledge to accept its
bid.
The bankruptcy judge acknowledged the role Martin Marietta had played in the
sale process, but declined to approve a Dollars 10m fee, suggesting Dollars
5m instead.
The sale is probably one of the last dramas in the LTV bankruptcy, which has
run for over five years. The company devised a reorganisation plan earlier
this year which is likely to win creditor approval, but the sale of these
businesses was a prerequisite to its adoption.
If the reorganisation scheme goes ahead, LTV would emerge from bankruptcy as
the nation's third largest steel maker and a major supplier of oilfield
equipment.
</TEXT>
